# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: colorado-territory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:colorado-territory/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:colorado-territory/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] The **1st Colorado Infantry Regiment** (officially the **1st Regiment of Colorado Volunteers**) was a volunteer infantry regiment of the United States Army formed in the Colorado Territory in 1861 and active in the American West in the late 19th century.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] The regiment was formed shortly after the outbreak of the American Civil War by order of William Gilpin, the first governor of the territory.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] Recruiters began enlisting men in August 1861, just six months after the organization of the territory.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] Known as "Gilpin's Pet Lambs" for the involvement of the governor in its formation, the regiment served in the Western Theater, at first serving in various detachments throughout the territory.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] The regiment's most notable service came in the New Mexico Campaign in the spring of 1862, in which they helped repulse the advance of the Army of New Mexico under Henry Hopkins Sibley at the battles of Glorieta Pass and Peralta.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] In November 1862, the unit was reorganized along with Companies C and D of the 2nd Colorado Infantry into the 1st Colorado Cavalry.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] The first colonel of the regiment was John P.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] Slough, replaced in April 1862 by Major John Chivington, later chastised for his role as commander of the 3rd Colorado Cavalry in the November 1864 Sand Creek Massacre.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] There is a group of reenactors who portray the First Colorado (Company D) in Denver.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] The regiment carried an 34 star American flag that measured 48 by 105.5 inches.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] The flag was given to the regiment on November 10, 1861 by secretary Weld at Fort Weld.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] It was carried thought-out New Mexico Territory during the war.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] During the Battle of Glorieta Pass the flag was hit by enemy fire which left a hole near the canton.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] After the battle the regiment was given a new flag.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] Company A had their own flag it given to them in August of 1861.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] It was an American flag with 34 golden stars in the canton.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] Brown, daughters of Captain Richard Sopris, and Miss Taylor.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] After the war it was given to Captain Sopris.
[src:colorado-territory/1st-colorado-infantry] When he died, his widow presented it to the adjutant generate office in 1904.
[src:colorado-territory/36th-united-states-congress] The **36th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:colorado-territory/36th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C. from March 4, 1859, to March 4, 1861, during the third and fourth years of James Buchanan's presidency.
[src:colorado-territory/36th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1850 United States census.
[src:colorado-territory/36th-united-states-congress] The Senate had a Democratic majority, and the House had a Republican plurality.
[src:colorado-territory/36th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:colorado-territory/36th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:colorado-territory/36th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:colorado-territory/36th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:colorado-territory/36th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring reelection in 1862; Class 2 meant their term began with this Congress, requiring reelection in 1864; and Class 3 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring reelection in 1860.
[src:colorado-territory/36th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:colorado-territory/36th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:colorado-territory/36th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Outpatient abortion is available up to 26 weeks.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In addition, medically indicated termination of pregnancy up to term is also an option for conditions such as fetal anomalies, genetic disorder, fetal demise and/or severe medical problems.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] 2024 Colorado Amendment 79 appeared on the ballot in November 2024.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] The amendment was approved, explicitly conferring a right to abortion in the Colorado state constitution.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 1962, the American Law Institute published their model penal code as it applied to abortions with three circumstances where they believed a physician could justifiably perform an abortion.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] A version of this was enacted into law in 1967.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Colorado became the first state to decriminalize abortion in cases of rape, incest, or in which pregnancy would lead to permanent physical disability of the woman.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] The first documented time "abortion" was mentioned in Colorado newspapers was in the Rocky Mountain News on September 30, 1867.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Back then, midwives used herbs to try to end pregnancies, but this could be very dangerous.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] The first documented arrest for abortion is J.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Mary Solander from Boulder was the first person sentenced to prison for abortion in 1873.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 1891, Colorado adopted Senate Bill 310, which further criminalized procuring an abortion.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In the early 1900s, newspapers reported more cases of doctors being charged.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 1909, osteopaths were prohibited from performing abortions.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 1929, the Colorado Assembly tried to make it legal for doctors to talk to married couples about birth control.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] But this law was killed in the Colorado Senate after heated debate.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] The proposed law was a partial repeal of the 1873 Comstock Act that made it illegal to distribute birth control materials.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Specifically, the new law permitted an abortion in cases of rape, incest, fetal abnormality, and to protect the life of the mother.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] However, it was only up to 16 weeks of pregnancy and required the husband's permission and approval from three doctors.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Over 33 months, 1,500 Colorado women obtained legal abortions, while around 20,000 sought illegal abortions because of the costs and red tape.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 1969, lawmakers failed to pass a bill that would have removed liability for a doctor or hospital refusing to perform an abortion.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 1973, the US Supreme Court's decision in *Roe v.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Wade* ruling meant the state could no longer regulate abortion in the first trimester.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In the period between 1972 and 1974, there were zero recorded illegal abortion deaths in the state.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] During the winter of 1978, three women in less than a month required hospitalization in Denver after consuming pennyroyal oil for the purpose of trying to induce an abortion.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 1978, Colorado set up Medicaid funding to help poor women get abortions.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 1979, a bill to ban public funding of abortions failed.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 1984, voters approved a similar constitutional amendment.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Between 1982 and 1992, the number of abortion clinics in the state decreased by fourteen, going from 73 in 1982 to 59 in 1992.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 1993, Colorado enacted speech restrictions within 100 feet of abortion clinics, a policy the U.S.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Colorado Republicans introduced numerous bills to ban or restrict abortion in almost all cases, beginning in 1997 and continuing through 2025.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] These bills did not pass due to Democratic opposition.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 2025, proposed bills backed by Republicans to ban abortion and prosecute women that had abortions were defeated.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 1998, Becky Bell's parents worked against proposed parental notification laws in Colorado.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 2006, pharmacists in Colorado were allowed to provide emergency contraception.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 2008, Colorado's Department of Public Health and Environment was provided with private funds to provide poor women in the state with long-acting reversible contraceptives (LARCs) at little or no cost to them.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] From 2009 to 2017, free, low-cost IUDs resulted in a 54% decline in the rate of teenage pregnancy in the state.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 2014, there were 21 abortion clinics in the state, and 78% of the counties in the state did not have an abortion clinic.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] That year, 27% of women in the state aged 15 – 44 lived in a county without an abortion clinic.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 2008, Kristine Burton and Michael Burton of Colorado for Equal Rights jointly proposed the Colorado Amendment 48 initiative.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Colorado Right to Life supported the amendment.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] The text would have amended the definition of a person to "any human being from the moment of fertilization".
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] This definition would have applied to all sections of Colorado law, thus giving a fetus the equal rights of life, liberty, and property as a fully developed, born person would.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] On November 4, 2008, the initiative was turned down by 73.2 percent of the voters.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Colorado Proposition 115 was a 2020 ballot initiative preventing abortion after 22 weeks unless the pregnancy endangered the mother's life.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Performing an abortion after 22 weeks would have become a Class 1 misdemeanor.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] On November 3, 2020, Colorado voters rejected Proposition 115, with 59% of voters opposed to the initiative.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In March 2016, there were 21 Planned Parenthood clinics in the state.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] After Planned Parenthood of the Rocky Mountains switched from directly billing women to directly billing Medicaid in 2016, it ran into funding bills as Medicaid has low reimbursement rates.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Consequently, it was forced to close two clinics in Colorado and one in Wyoming in July 2017.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 2017, there were nineteen Planned Parenthood clinics, of which eleven offered abortion services, in a state with a population of 1,278,937 women aged 15–49.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 2019, women in Colorado were eligible for temporary disability as a result of abortion or miscarriage.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] On April 4, 2022, Governor Jared Polis signed the Reproductive Health Equity Act, which guarantees access to reproductive care and affirms the rights of pregnant women to continue or terminate a pregnancy.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] The act prohibits public entities from restricting or denying those rights.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, No.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] On April 18, 2024, Coloradans For Protecting Reproductive Freedom submitted nearly double the signatures required to put abortion rights on the ballot in Colorado in the November 2024 elections.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] 2024 Colorado Amendment 79 enshrined the right to abortion in the Colorado state constitution.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] 59% of adults said in a 2014 Pew Research Center poll that abortion should be legal in all or most cases and 36% said it should be illegal in all or most cases.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] The 2023 American Values Atlas reported that, in their most recent survey, 65% of Coloradans said that abortion should be legal in all or most cases.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 1990, 426,000 women in the state faced the risk of an unintended pregnancy.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Since the start of the 2008 Colorado Family Planning Initiative, the number of abortions performed in the state fell by nearly half for women between the ages of 15–19.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] For women aged 20–24, the rate of abortions declined by 18%.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] For teens aged 15–19, the birth and abortion rate in Colorado between 2009 and 2014 declined around 50%.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] For women aged 20–24, the abortion rate declined by 20%.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 2010, the state had no publicly funded abortions.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 2013, there were 700 abortions for white women aged 15–19, 110 abortions for black women aged 15–19, 470 abortions for Hispanic women aged 15–19, and 90 abortions for women of all other races.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 2014, 59% of adults said in a poll by the Pew Research Center that abortion should be legal and 36% saying it should be illegal in all or most cases.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In 2017, the state had an infant mortality rate of 4.5 deaths per 1,000 live births.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] From 2009 to 2017, the rate of teenage abortions in the state fell by 64%.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In state politics, the Colorado Democratic Party largely support access to abortion and have passed legislation to protect and increase the accessibility of the procedure.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Women from the state participated in marches supporting abortion rights as part of a #StoptheBans movement in May 2019.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Wade overturn draft leak on May 2, 2022, there were abortion rights demonstrations in Aspen, Colorado Springs, Denver, Fort Collins, and Grand Junction.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Wade on June 24, 2022, an abortion rights protest was held outside the Colorado State Capitol in Denver.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In state politics, the Colorado Republican Party has embraced hardline anti-abortion stances which have included proposing laws to restrict or even ban abortion in the state.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Several hundred anti-abortion activists participate in the Rocky Mountain March for Life in Colorado each year to support ending abortion.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Respect Life Denver also organizes an annual rally and march in the state capitol each year to support legislation against abortion.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Since 2024, there has been increased reports of anti-abortion protestors trespassing, threatening and obstructing access to abortion clinics.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In late 2022, four out of seven council members of the city of Pueblo voted to consider a measure that would ban abortion within the city.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] The proposed ordinance was the work of a Texas-based anti-abortion group which was introduced by council member Regina Maestri.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] The proposed measure would break state laws surrounding abortion protections while observers said the measure might inspire other cities or towns throughout Colorado to attempt to ban or restrict abortions.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] The measure was narrowly rejected by the council.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] In October 2024, there was another attempt to ban abortion in Pueblo by conservative council members.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] The measure was again narrowly defeated.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] An incident of anti-abortion violence occurred at an abortion clinic in Denver, Colorado on August 26, 2003.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Between 1993 and 2015, 11 people were killed at American abortion clinics.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] On November 29, 2015, a shooting at a Planned Parenthood clinic in Colorado Springs, Colorado, left three dead and several injured, and a suspect, Robert L.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Police officer and pastor Garrett Swasey, US Iraq War veteran Ke'Arre M.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Stewart, and Hawaiian Jennifer Markovsky, who was accompanying a friend at the clinic, were killed.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] The suspect had previously acted against other clinics, and referred to himself as a "warrior for the babies" at his hearing.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] Neighbors and former neighbors described the suspect as "reclusive", and police from several states where the suspect resided described a history of run-ins dating from at least 1997.
[src:colorado-territory/abortion-in-colorado] On May 11, 2016, the court declared the suspect incompetent to stand trial after a mental evaluation was completed.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky, Lincoln was raised on the frontier.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was self-educated and became a lawyer, Illinois state legislator, and U.S. representative.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Angered by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854, which opened the territories to slavery, he became a leader of the new Republican Party.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He reached a national audience in the 1858 Senate campaign debates against Stephen A.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election, becoming the first Republican president.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory prompted a majority of the slave states to begin seceding and form the Confederate States.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] A month after Lincoln assumed the presidency, Confederate forces attacked Fort Sumter, starting the Civil War.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] As a moderate Republican, Lincoln had to navigate conflicting political opinions from contentious factions during the war effort.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He closely supervised the Union's strategy and tactics, including the selection of generals and the implementation of a naval blockade of Southern ports.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He suspended the writ of *habeas corpus* in April 1861, an action that Chief Justice Roger Taney found in *Ex parte Merryman* that only Congress could do, and he averted war with Britain by defusing the *Trent* Affair.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 1, 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared the slaves in the states "in rebellion" to be free.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 19, 1863, he delivered the Gettysburg Address, which became one of the most famous speeches in American history.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He promoted the Thirteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Constitution, which, in 1865, abolished chattel slavery.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Following his re-election in 1864, he sought to heal the war-torn nation through Reconstruction.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] On April 14, 1865, five days after the Confederate surrender at Appomattox, Lincoln was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in Washington, D.C., becoming the first U.S. president to be assassinated.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln is remembered as a martyr and a national hero for his wartime leadership and for his efforts to preserve the Union and abolish slavery.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He is consistently ranked in both popular and scholarly polls as among the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky on February 12, 1809, Abraham Lincoln was raised on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The captain was killed in a Native American raid in 1786.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The family settled in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nancy is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] They had three children: Sarah, Abraham, and Thomas Jr., who died as an infant.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's father bought multiple farms in Kentucky but could not get clear property titles to any, losing hundreds of acres in legal disputes.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where land titles were more reliable.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] They settled on a forested plot in Little Pigeon Creek Community.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] At various times, he owned farms, livestock, and town lots, appraised estates, and served on county patrols.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptist Church, a pious evangelical group whose members largely opposed slavery.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) in Little Pigeon Creek Community in 1827.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] On October 5, 1818, Nancy died from milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of the household, which included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Nancy's 19-year-old orphan cousin, Dennis Hanks.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas married Sarah Bush Johnston, a widow with three children of her own, on December 2, 1819.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became close to his stepmother and called her "Mama".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 20, 1828, Lincoln's sister died in childbirth, devastating him.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] His formal schooling was from itinerant teachers.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] It included two short stints in Kentucky, where he learned to read, but probably not to write.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] After moving to Indiana at age seven, he attended school only sporadically, for a total of less than 12 months by age 15.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nevertheless, he was an avid reader and maintained a lifelong interest in learning.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln was a teenager his father relied heavily on him for farmwork and for supplementary income, hiring the boy out to area farmers and pocketing the money, as was the custom at the time.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] When he was somewhat older, Lincoln and some friends took a job carrying goods by flatboat to New Orleans, Louisiana, where the slave markets, according to the historian Michael Burlingame, "would leave an indelible impression on him....
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In March 1830, fearing another milk-sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family, including Abraham, moved west to Illinois and settled in Macon County.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part due to his father's lack of interest in education; he would later refuse to attend his father's deathbed or funeral in 1851.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Some historians, such as Michael Burlingame, identify Lincoln's first romantic interest as Ann Rutledge, a young woman also from Kentucky whom he met when he moved to New Salem, Illinois.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lewis Gannett disputes that the evidence supports a romantic relationship between the two.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] David Herbert Donald states that "How that friendship [between Lincoln and Rutledge] developed into a romance cannot be reconstructed from the record".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rutledge died on August 25, 1835, of typhoid fever.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln took her death very hard, sinking into a serious depression and contemplating suicide.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the early 1830s, Lincoln met Mary Owens from Kentucky.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to a match with Owens if she returned to New Salem.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Owens arrived that November and he courted her, but they both had second thoughts.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] On August 16, 1837, he wrote Owens a letter saying he would not blame her if she ended the relationship, and she declined to marry him.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1839, Lincoln met Mary Todd in Springfield, Illinois, and the following year they became engaged.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] She was a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy lawyer and businessman in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln initially broke off the engagement in early 1841, but the two were reconciled and married on November 4, 1842.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near his law office.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The marriage was turbulent; Mary was verbally abusive and at times physically violent towards her husband.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The eldest, Robert Todd Lincoln, was born in 1843, and was the only child to live to maturity.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Edward Baker "Eddie" Lincoln, born in 1846, died February 1, 1850, probably of tuberculosis.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's third son, William Wallace "Willie" Lincoln, was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever at the White House on February 20, 1862.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The youngest, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of edema at age 18 on July 16, 1871.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln loved children, and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The deaths of Eddie and Willie had profound effects on both parents.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln suffered from "melancholy", a condition now thought to be clinical depression.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1831, Lincoln's father moved the family to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, after which Abraham struck out on his own.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He made his home in New Salem, Illinois, for six years.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] During 1831 and 1832, Lincoln worked at a general store in New Salem.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He gained a reputation for strength and courage after winning a wrestling match with the leader of a group of ruffians known as the Clary's Grove boys.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1832, he declared his candidacy for the Illinois House of Representatives, though he interrupted his campaign to serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the Black Hawk War.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was elected the captain of his militia company but did not see combat.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his political campaigning, Lincoln advocated for navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He drew crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked name recognition, powerful friends, and money, and he lost the election.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln returned home from the war, he planned to become a blacksmith but instead purchased a New Salem general store in partnership with William Berry.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Because a license was required to sell customers alcoholic beverages, Berry obtained bartending licenses for Lincoln and himself, and in 1833 the Lincoln–Berry General Store became a tavern as well.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Burlingame wrote that Berry was "an undisciplined, hard-drinking fellow", and Lincoln "was too soft-hearted to deny anyone credit".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and went into debt, prompting Lincoln to sell his share.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, but he continued his voracious reading and decided to become a lawyer.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rather than studying in the office of an established attorney, as was customary, Lincoln read law on his own, borrowing legal texts, including Blackstone's *Commentaries* and Chitty's *Pleadings*, from attorney John Todd Stuart.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He later said of his legal education that he "studied with nobody." He was bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Laws by Columbia University in 1861.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Lincoln's second state house campaign in 1834, as a supporter of Whig Party leader Henry Clay, he finished second among thirteen candidates running for four places.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln echoed Clay's support for the American Colonization Society, which advocated abolition in conjunction with settling freed slaves in Liberia.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Whigs also favored economic modernization in banking, tariffs to fund internal improvements such as railroads, and urbanization.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served four terms in the Illinois House of Representatives for Sangamon County.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this role, he championed construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln voted to expand suffrage beyond White landowners to all White men.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the chartering of the Illinois State Bank, and also led a successful campaign for moving the state capital from Vandalia to Springfield.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 27, 1838, Lincoln delivered an address at the Lyceum in Springfield, after the murder of the anti-slavery newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this ostensibly non-partisan speech, Lincoln attacked Stephen A.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas and the Democratic Party, who the Whigs argued were supporting "mobocracy".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] His speech also attacked anti-abolitionism and racial bigotry.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was criticized in the press for a planned duel with James Shields, whom he had ridiculed in letters published under the name "Aunt Rebecca".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the duel did not take place, Burlingame noted that "the affair embarrassed Lincoln terribly".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1843, Lincoln sought the Whig nomination for Illinois's 7th district seat in the U.S.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Hardin was the winning candidate, though Lincoln convinced the party convention to limit Hardin to one term.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln not only gained the nomination in 1846, but also won the election.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The only Whig in the Illinois delegation, he was assigned to the Committee on Post Office and Post Roads and the Committee on Expenditures in the War Department.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Giddings on a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia, but dropped the bill when it failed to attract support from most other Whigs.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln spoke against the Mexican–American War (1846–1848), for which he said President James K.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk had "some strong motive ... to involve the two countries in a war, and trusting to escape scrutiny, by fixing the public gaze upon the exceeding brightness of military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the Wilmot Proviso, a failed 1846 proposal to ban slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had begun the war by "invading the territory of the State of Texas ... and shedding the blood of our citizens on our own soil".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his 1847 "spot resolutions", Lincoln rhetorically demanded that Polk tell Congress the exact "spot" where this occurred, but the Polk administration did not respond.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] His approach and rhetoric cost Lincoln political support in his district, and newspapers derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the 1848 Whig National Convention, he initially supported Henry Clay and was among the leaders of the Illinois delegation backing Clay, voting for him on the early ballots.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] When it became clear that Clay could not secure the nomination, Lincoln joined other Whigs in shifting support to Zachary Taylor, who won the party's nomination and the presidency in 1848.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Taylor won, Lincoln hoped in vain to be appointed commissioner of the United States General Land Office.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The administration offered to appoint him secretary of the Oregon Territory instead.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] This would have disrupted his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was admitted to the Illinois bar on September 9, 1836.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He moved to Springfield and began to practice law under John T.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He partnered for several years with Stephen T.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Logan and, in 1844, began his practice with William Herndon.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Springfield practice, according to Donald, Lincoln handled "virtually every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He dealt with many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly river barge conflicts under the new railroad bridges.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1849 he received a patent for a flotation device for the movement of riverboats in shallow water and Lincoln initially favored riverboat legal interests, but he represented whoever hired him.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He represented a bridge company against a riverboat company in *Hurd v.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rock Island Bridge Company*, a landmark case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] His patent was never commercialized, but it made Lincoln the only president to hold a patent.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 411 cases.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] From 1853 to 1860, one of his largest clients was the Illinois Central Railroad, which Lincoln successfully sued to recover his legal fees.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln represented William "Duff" Armstrong in his 1858 trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by judicial notice to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] After a witness testified to seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a *Farmers' Almanac* showing the Moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In an 1859 murder case, he defended "Peachy" Quinn Harrison, the grandson of Peter Cartwright, Lincoln's political opponent.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Harrison was charged with the murder of Greek Crafton who, according to Cartwright, said as he lay dying that he had "brought it upon myself" and that he forgave Harrison.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln angrily protested the judge's initial decision to exclude Cartwright's claim as hearsay.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln argued that the testimony involved a dying declaration and so was not subject to the hearsay rule.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as expected, the judge, a Democrat, admitted the testimony into evidence, resulting in Harrison's acquittal.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Compromise of 1850 failed to alleviate tensions over slavery between the slave-holding South and the free North.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the slavery debate in the Nebraska and Kansas territories became particularly acrimonious, Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas proposed popular sovereignty as a compromise; the measure would allow the electorate of each territory to decide the status of slavery.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The legislation alarmed many Northerners, who sought to prevent the spread of slavery, but Douglas's Kansas–Nebraska Act narrowly passed Congress in May 1854.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's Peoria Speech of October 1854, in which he declared his opposition to slavery, was one of an estimated 175 speeches he delivered in the next six years on the topic of excluding slavery from the territories.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's attacks on the Kansas–Nebraska Act marked his return to political life.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nationally, the Whigs were irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act and other ineffective efforts to compromise on the slavery issue.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Reflecting on the demise of his party, Lincoln wrote in 1855, "I think I am a whig; but others say there are no whigs, and that I am an abolitionist....
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] I now do no more than oppose the *extension* of slavery." The new Republican Party was formed as a northern party dedicated to anti-slavery, drawing from the anti-slavery wing of the Whig Party and combining Free Soil, Liberty, and anti-slavery Democratic Party members.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln resisted early Republican entreaties, fearing that the new party would become a platform for extreme abolitionists.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln held out hope for rejuvenating the Whigs, though he lamented his party's growing closeness with the nativist Know Nothing movement.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1854, Lincoln was elected to the Illinois legislature, but before the term began he declined to take his seat so that he would be eligible to run in the upcoming U.S.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] At that time, senators were elected by state legislatures.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] After leading in the first six rounds of voting, Lincoln was unable to obtain a majority.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for Lyman Trumbull, an anti-slavery Democrat who had received few votes in the earlier ballots.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's decision to withdraw enabled his Whig supporters and Trumbull's anti-slavery Democrats to combine and defeat the mainstream Democratic candidate, Joel Aldrich Matteson.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Violent political confrontations in Kansas continued, and opposition to the Kansas–Nebraska Act remained strong throughout the North.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the 1856 elections approached, Lincoln joined the Republicans and attended the Bloomington Convention, where the Illinois Republican Party was established.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The convention platform endorsed Congress's right to regulate slavery in the territories and backed the admission of Kansas as a free state.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln gave the final speech of the convention, calling for the preservation of the Union.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the June 1856 Republican National Convention, Lincoln received support to run as vice president, but the party put forward a ticket of John C.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Frémont and William Dayton, which Lincoln supported throughout Illinois.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Democrats nominated James Buchanan and the Know Nothings nominated Millard Fillmore.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Buchanan prevailed, while Republican William Henry Bissell won election as Governor of Illinois, and Lincoln became a leading Republican in Illinois.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Dred Scott was a slave whose master took him from a slave state to a territory that was free as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Scott was returned to the slave state, he petitioned a federal court for his freedom.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] His petition was denied in *Dred Scott v.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Taney wrote in his opinion that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional because it infringed on slave owners' property rights by prohibiting them from bringing their slaves into the territories.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] While many Democrats hoped that *Dred Scott* would end the dispute over slavery in the territories, the decision sparked further outrage in the North.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln denounced it as the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He argued that the decision was at variance with the Declaration of Independence, which stated that "all men are created equal ... with certain unalienable rights", among them "life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1858, Douglas was up for re-election in the U.S.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Senate, and Lincoln hoped to defeat him.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the party felt that a former Whig should be nominated in 1858, and Lincoln's 1856 campaigning and support of Trumbull had earned him a favor.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] For the first time, Illinois Republicans held a convention to agree upon a Senate candidate, and Lincoln won the nomination with little opposition.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln accepted the nomination with great enthusiasm and zeal.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The speech created a stark image of the danger of disunion.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Senate campaign featured seven debates between Lincoln and Douglas; they had an atmosphere akin to a prizefight and drew thousands.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln warned that the Slave Power was threatening the values of republicanism, and he accused Douglas of distorting Jefferson's premise that all men are created equal.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Freeport Doctrine, Douglas argued that, despite the *Dred Scott* decision, which he claimed to support, local settlers, under popular sovereignty, should be free to choose whether to allow slavery in their territory.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] However, Lincoln's articulation of the issues had given him a national political presence.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the aftermath of the 1858 election, newspapers frequently mentioned Lincoln as a potential Republican presidential candidate.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] While Lincoln was popular in the Midwest, he lacked support in the Northeast and was unsure whether to seek the office.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In January 1860, Lincoln told a group of political allies that he would accept the presidential nomination if offered and, in the following months, William O.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Stoddard's *Central Illinois Gazette*, the *Chicago Press & Tribune*, and other local papers endorsed his candidacy.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In February 1860, Henry Ward Beecher invited Lincoln to address his congregation at Plymouth Church in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln agreed, but the venue shifted to Cooper Union in Manhattan.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the audience thought he appeared awkward and even ugly.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] But Lincoln demonstrated intellectual leadership, which brought him into contention for the presidency.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Journalist Noah Brooks reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Historian David Herbert Donald described the speech as "a superb political move for an unannounced presidential aspirant." In response to an inquiry about his ambitions, Lincoln said, "The taste *is* in my mouth a little".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in Decatur.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Exploiting his embellished frontier legend of clearing land and splitting fence rails, Lincoln's supporters promoted him as "The Rail Candidate".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 18 at the Republican National Convention in Chicago, Lincoln won the nomination on the third ballot.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] A former Democrat, Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was nominated for vice president to balance the ticket.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln had doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, delegates from the Southern slave states elected incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party and nominated John Bell of Tennessee.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln and Douglas competed for votes in the North, while Bell and Breckinridge found support primarily in the South.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] A nationwide militaristic Republican youth organization, the Wide Awakes, "turned it into one of the most excited elections in American history" and "triggered massive popular enthusiasm", according to the political historian Jon Grinspan.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] People of the Northern states knew the Southern states would vote against Lincoln and rallied supporters for him.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] As Douglas and the other candidates campaigned, Lincoln gave no speeches, relying on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Republican speakers emphasized Lincoln's childhood poverty to demonstrate the power of "free labor", which allowed a common farm boy to work his way to the top by his own efforts.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though he did not make public appearances, many sought to visit and write to Lincoln.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the runup to the election, he took an office in the Illinois state capitol to deal with the influx of attention.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] He also hired John George Nicolay as his personal secretary, who would remain in that role during the presidency.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected as the first Republican president.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory was entirely due to his support in the North and West.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] No ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, or 39.8 percent of the total in a four-way race, carrying the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon, and winning the electoral vote decisively.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] above the rotunda still under construction.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] following Lincoln's first inauguration portended imminent hostilities.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Lincoln's election, secessionists implemented plans to leave the Union before he took office in March 1861.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] On December 20, 1860, South Carolina adopted an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas had followed.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Six of these states declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the Confederate States of America, selecting Jefferson Davis as its provisional president.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) initially rejected the secessionist appeal.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 11, 1861, Lincoln gave a particularly emotional farewell address upon leaving Springfield for Washington.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and the Republicans rejected the proposed Crittenden Compromise as contrary to the party's platform of free-soil in the territories.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln said, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln supported the Corwin Amendment to the U.S.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Constitution, which would have protected slavery in states where it already existed.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The amendment passed Congress and was awaiting ratification by the required three-fourths of the states when Southern states began to secede.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] On March 4, 1861, in his first inaugural address, Lincoln said that, because he held "such a provision to now be implied constitutional law, I have no objection to its being made express, and irrevocable".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Due to secessionist plots, careful attention was paid to Lincoln's security and the train he took to Washington.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president-elect evaded suspected assassins in Baltimore.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] He traveled in disguise, wearing a soft felt hat instead of his customary stovepipe hat and draping an overcoat over his shoulders while hunching to conceal his height.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 23, 1861, he arrived in Washington, D.C., which was placed under military guard.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many in the opposition press criticized his secretive journey; opposition newspapers mocked Lincoln with caricatures showing him sneaking into the capital.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends....
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battle-field, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone ... will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched ... by the better angels of our nature".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Donald, the failure of the Peace Conference of 1861 to attract the attendance of seven of the Confederate states signaled that legislative compromise was not a practical expectation.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In selecting his cabinet, Lincoln chose the men he found the most competent, even when they had been his opponents for the presidency.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln commented on his thought process, "We need the strongest men of the party in the Cabinet.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] We needed to hold our own people together.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] I had looked the party over and concluded that these were the very strongest men.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Then I had no right to deprive the country of their services." Doris Kearns Goodwin described the group in her 2005 biography of Lincoln as a "team of rivals".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln named his main political opponent, William H.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln made five appointments to the Supreme Court.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Noah Haynes Swayne, a prominent corporate lawyer from Ohio, replaced John McLean after the latter's death in April 1861.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Samuel Freeman Miller, who replaced Peter V.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Daniel, was an avowed abolitionist and received widespread support from Iowa politicians.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] David Davis was Lincoln's campaign manager in 1860 and had served as a judge in the Illinois court circuit where Lincoln practiced.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democrat Stephen Johnson Field, a previous California Supreme Court justice, provided geographic and political balance.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Taney, Lincoln appointed his former secretary of the treasury, Salmon P.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Chase, to replace Taney as chief justice.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln believed Chase was an able jurist who would support Reconstruction legislation and that his appointment would unite the Republican Party.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April 1861, Major Robert Anderson, commander of Fort Sumter in Charleston, South Carolina, advised that he was nearly out of food.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] After considerable deliberation, Lincoln decided to send provisions; according to Michael Burlingame, he "could not be sure that his decision would precipitate a war, though he had good reason to believe that it might".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at Fort Sumter, starting the American Civil War.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The April 12 and 13 attack on Fort Sumter rallied the Northern public to see military action against the South as necessary to defend the nation.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 15, Lincoln called for 75,000 militiamen to recapture forts, protect Washington, and preserve the Union.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] This call forced states to choose whether to secede or to support the Union.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] North Carolina, Virginia, Tennessee, and Arkansas seceded.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the Northern states sent regiments south, on April 19 Baltimore mobs in control of the rail links attacked Union troops who were changing trains.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Local leaders' groups later burned critical rail bridges to the capital and the Army responded by arresting local Maryland officials.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln suspended the writ of *habeas corpus*, allowing arrests without formal charges.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Merryman, a Maryland officer arrested for hindering U.S. troop movements, successfully petitioned Supreme Court Chief Justice Taney to issue a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In an opinion titled *Ex parte Merryman*, Taney, not ruling on behalf of the Supreme Court, wrote that the Constitution authorized only Congress and not the president to suspend habeas corpus.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] But Lincoln engaged in nonacquiescence and persisted with the policy of suspension in select areas.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Under various suspensions, 15,000 civilians were detained without trial; several, including the anti-war Democrat Clement L.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Vallandigham, were tried in military courts for "treasonable" actions, which was condemned as an attack on free speech.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln took executive control of the war and shaped the Union military strategy.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] He responded to the unprecedented political and military crisis as commander-in-chief by exercising unprecedented authority.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] He expanded his war powers, imposed a naval blockade on Confederate ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, suspended *habeas corpus*, and arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gained the support of Congress and the northern public for these actions.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also had to reinforce Union sympathies in the border slave states and keep the war from becoming an international conflict.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was clear from the outset that bipartisan support was essential to success, and that any compromise alienated factions in both political parties.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Copperheads (anti-war Democrats) criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on slavery; the Radical Republicans, who demanded harsh treatment against secession, criticized him for moving too slowly to abolish slavery.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the Confiscation Act, which authorized judicial proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederates.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law had little practical effect, but it signaled political support for abolishing slavery.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's war strategy had two priorities: ensuring that Washington was well defended and conducting an aggressive war effort for a prompt, decisive victory.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Twice a week, Lincoln met with his cabinet.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Occasionally, Lincoln's wife, Mary, prevailed on him to take a carriage ride, concerned that he was working too hard.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, Lincoln selected civilian generals from varied political and ethnic backgrounds "to secure their and their constituents' support for the war effort and ensure that the war became a national struggle".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In January 1862, after complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced Simon Cameron as secretary of war with Edwin Stanton.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stanton worked more often and more closely with Lincoln than did any other senior official.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Stanton's biographers Benjamin P.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Thomas and Harold Hyman, "Stanton and Lincoln virtually conducted the war together".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln saw the importance of Vicksburg for control of the Mississippi River valley and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than merely capturing territory.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In directing the Union's war strategy, Lincoln valued the advice of Winfield Scott, even after his retirement as Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1861 Scott proposed the Anaconda Plan, which relied on port blockades and advancing down the Mississippi to subdue the South.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In June 1862, Lincoln made an unannounced visit to West Point, where he spent five hours consulting with Scott regarding the handling of the war.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Internationally, Lincoln wanted to forestall foreign military aid to the Confederacy.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] He relied on his combative Secretary of State William Seward while working closely with Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Charles Sumner.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Navy illegally intercepted a British mail ship, the *RMS Trent*, on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although the North celebrated the seizure, Britain protested vehemently, and the Trent Affair threatened war between the Americans and the British.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ended the crisis by releasing the two diplomats.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union rout at Bull Run and Winfield Scott's retirement, Lincoln appointed George B.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, McClellan created defenses for Washington that were almost impregnable: 48 forts and batteries, with 480 guns manned by 7,200 artillerists.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] He spent months planning his Virginia Peninsula Campaign.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan's slow progress and excessive precautions frustrated Lincoln.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan, in turn, blamed the failure of the campaign on Lincoln's cautiousness in having reserved troops for the capital.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1862, Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief; he elevated Henry Halleck to the post and appointed John Pope as head of the new Army of Virginia.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the summer of 1862 Pope was soundly defeated at the Second Battle of Bull Run, forcing him to retreat to Washington.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Soon after, the Army of Virginia was disbanded.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln restored him to command of all forces around Washington, which included both the Army of the Potomac and the remains of the Army of Virginia.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the Battle of Antietam.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] This battle, a Union victory, was among the bloodiest in American history.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] A crisis of command occurred for Lincoln when McClellan then resisted the president's demand that he pursue Lee's withdrawing army, while Don Carlos Buell likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln replaced Buell with William Rosecrans and McClellan with Ambrose Burnside; according to Donald, this was a "shrewd" political move as they were non-partisan—unlike McClellan, a Democrat.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Against presidential advice, Burnside launched an offensive across the Rappahannock River and was defeated by Lee at Fredericksburg in December.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Facing low morale and discontent among the troops, Lincoln replaced Burnside with Joseph Hooker.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hooker endured heavy casualties at the Battle of Chancellorsville in May, then resigned in June and was replaced by George Meade.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Meade followed Lee north into Pennsylvania and defeated him in the Gettysburg campaign but then failed to effectively block Lee's orderly retreat to Virginia, despite Lincoln's demands.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant captured Vicksburg and gained control of the Mississippi River.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In May 1863, Lincoln issued the Lieber Code, which governed wartime conduct of the Union Army, defining command responsibility for war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two Union generals had issued emancipation orders in 1861 and 1862, but Lincoln overrode both: he found that the decision to emancipate was not within the generals' power, and that it might induce loyal border states to secede.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, in June 1862, Congress passed an act banning slavery in all federal territories, which Lincoln signed.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In July, the Confiscation Act of 1862 was enacted, allowing the seizure of slaves from those disloyal to the United States.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] On July 22, 1862, Lincoln reviewed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Senator Willard Saulsbury Sr. criticized the proclamation, stating that it "would light their author to dishonor through all future generations".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] By contrast, Horace Greeley, editor of the *New-York Tribune*, in his public letter, "The Prayer of Twenty Millions", implored Lincoln to embrace emancipation.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Buttressed by news of the recent Union victory at Antietam, on September 22, 1862, Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, which proclaimed that, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves within any state still in rebellion would be free.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] On January 1, 1863, he issued the final Emancipation Proclamation, freeing the slaves in the ten states not then under Union control, exempting areas under such control.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] With the abolition of slavery in the rebel states now a military objective, Union armies advancing south enabled thousands to escape bondage.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Proclamation was immediately denounced by Copperheads, who advocated restoring the union by allowing slavery.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was also seen as a betrayal of his promise to Southern Unionists not to tamper with slavery; Emerson Etheridge, then Clerk of the House of Representatives, joined an unsuccessful plot to give the Democrats and Southern Unionists control of the House.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a result of the Proclamation, enlisting freedmen became official policy.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In a letter to Tennessee military governor Andrew Johnson, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of fifty thousand armed, and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gave the dedication for the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery on November 19, 1863.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The address became the most quoted speech in American history.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Following Admiral David Farragut's capture of New Orleans in 1862, and after victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg, Lincoln proclaimed a national Thanksgiving holiday, to be celebrated on the final Thursday of November 1863.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's victories at the Battle of Shiloh and in the Vicksburg campaign impressed Lincoln.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln said, "I can't spare this man.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] He fights." Following Meade's failure to capture Lee's army after Gettysburg and after Grant's success at Chattanooga, Lincoln promoted Grant to commander of all Union armies.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln reacted to Union losses by mobilizing support throughout the North.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union forces targeted infrastructure—plantations, railroads, and bridges—to weaken the South's morale and fighting ability.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] While Lincoln sanctioned this approach, he emphasized the defeat of the Confederate armies over destruction for its own sake.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody Overland Campaign turned into a strategic success for the Union despite a number of setbacks.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] But the campaign was the bloodiest in American history: approximately 55,000 casualties on the Union side (including 7,600 deaths), compared to about 33,000 on the Confederate (including 4,200 deaths).
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's losses, although lower in absolute numbers, were proportionately higher (over 50%) than Grant's (about 45%).
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April, the Confederate government evacuated Richmond and Lincoln visited the conquered capital.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Amid the turmoil of military actions, on June 30, 1864, Lincoln signed into law the Yosemite Grant, which provided unprecedented federal protection for the area now known as Yosemite National Park.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and Secretary of the Treasury Salmon Chase faced a challenge in funding a wartime economy.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress quickly approved Lincoln's request to assemble an army, even increasing his proposed 400,000 soldiers to 500,000, but both Congress and Chase initially resisted raising taxes.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run, which collapsed the bond market, Congress passed the Revenue Act of 1861.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] This act imposed the first U.S. federal income tax, creating a flat tax of three percent on annual incomes above $800 ($28,700 in current dollars).
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the average urban worker made approximately $600 per year, many were not required to pay income taxes.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also signed increases to the Morrill Tariff, which had become law in the final months of Buchanan's tenure.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] These tariffs raised import duties considerably and were designed both to increase revenue and to help manufacturers offset the burden of new taxes.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Throughout the war, Congress debated whether to raise additional revenue primarily by increasing tariff rates, which most strongly affected rural areas, or by increasing income taxes, which most affected wealthier individuals; the latter view proved more popular.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The revenue measures of 1861 proved inadequate for funding the war, forcing Congress to take further action.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In February 1862, Congress passed the Legal Tender Act, which authorized the minting of $150 million in "greenbacks"—the first banknotes issued by the U.S. government since the end of the American Revolution.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Greenbacks were not backed by gold or silver, but rather by the government's promise to honor their value.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, $450 million worth of greenbacks were in circulation.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress also passed the Revenue Act of 1862, which established an excise tax affecting nearly every commodity, as well as the first national inheritance tax.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] It also added a progressive tax structure to the federal income tax.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] To collect these taxes, Congress created the Office of the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite the new revenue measures, funding the war remained challenging.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The government continued to issue greenbacks and borrow large amounts of money, and the U.S. national debt grew from $65 million in 1860 to over $2 billion in 1866.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Revenue Act of 1864 represented a compromise between those who favored a more progressive tax structure and those who favored a flat tax.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] It established a five-percent tax on incomes above $600 and a ten-percent tax on incomes above $10,000, and it raised taxes on businesses.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early 1865, Congress reduced the threshold for ten-percent taxation to incomes above $5000.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, the income tax constituted about one-fifth of the federal government's revenue, though it was intended as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also took action against wartime fraud, signing into law the False Claims Act of 1863.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] This statute imposed penalties for false claims and made it possible for private citizens to file false-claim (*qui tam*) lawsuits on behalf of the U.S. government and share in the recovery.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hoping to stabilize the currency, Lincoln convinced Congress to pass the National Banking Act in 1863, established the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to oversee "national banks," which were subject to federal, rather than state, regulation.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In return for investing a third of their capital in federal bonds, national banks were authorized to issue federal banknotes.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Congress imposed a tax on private banknotes in March 1865, federal banknotes became the dominant form of paper currency.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Other economic policies passed under Lincoln included the 1862 Homestead Act, which made millions of acres of government-held land in the West available for purchase at low cost.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The 1862 Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act provided government grants for agricultural colleges in each state.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Pacific Railway Acts of 1862 and 1864 granted federal support for the construction of the United States' first transcontinental railroad, which was completed in 1869.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the start of the war, Russia was the lone great power to support the Union, while the other European powers had varying degrees of sympathy for the Confederacy.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to the historian Dean Mahin, Lincoln had "limited familiarity with diplomatic practices" but exerted "substantial influence on U.S. diplomacy" as the Union attempted to avoid war with Britain and France.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln appointed diplomats to try to persuade European nations not to recognize the Confederacy.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policy succeeded: all foreign nations were officially neutral throughout the Civil War, with none recognizing the Confederacy.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some European leaders looked for ways to exploit the inability of the U.S. to enforce the Monroe Doctrine opposing European colonial intervention in the Americas: Spain invaded the Dominican Republic in 1861, while France established a puppet regime in Mexico.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, many in Europe also hoped for a quick end to the war, both for humanitarian reasons and because of the economic disruption it caused.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed", according to Don H.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union diplomats initially had to explain that the United States was not committed to ending slavery, and instead they argued that secession was unconstitutional.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Confederate spokesmen were more successful by ignoring slavery and instead focusing on their struggle for independence, their commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Confederacy's hope that cotton exports would compel European interference did not come to fruition, as Britain found alternative sources and maintained economic ties with the Union.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Though the issuance of the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863 did not immediately end the possibility of European intervention, it rallied European public opinion to the Union by adding abolition as a Union war goal.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Any chance of a European intervention in the war ended with the Union victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg in July 1863, as European leaders came to believe that the Confederate cause was doomed.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Dole as commissioner of the Bureau of Indian Affairs and made "extensive use of Indian Service positions to reward political supporters", according to the historian Thomas Britten.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policies largely focused on assimilation of Native Americans and diminishing tribal landholdings, consistent with those of his predecessors, but his direct involvement in Native American affairs was unclear.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] His administration faced difficulties guarding Western settlers, railroads, and telegraph lines from Native American attacks.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Tensions arose with the Dakota people due to American treaty violations, unfair trading, and government practices that led to starvation.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In August 1862, the Dakota War broke out in Minnesota.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hundreds of settlers were killed and 30,000 were displaced from their homes.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some feared incorrectly that it might represent a Confederate conspiracy to start a war on the Northwestern frontier.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ordered thousands of paroled prisoners of war be sent to put down the uprising.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] When the Confederacy protested, Lincoln revoked the policy and none arrived in Minnesota.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln sent Pope as commander of the new Department of the Northwest.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Appointed as a state militia colonel, Henry Hastings Sibley eventually defeated the Dakota chief Little Crow at the Battle of Wood Lake.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] A war crimes trial led by Sibley sentenced 303 Dakota warriors to death; the legal scholar Carol Chomsky described the trial as "a study in military injustice" designed to "guarantee an unjust outcome".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln pardoned all but 39 of the condemned warriors, and, with one execution suspended, the remaining 38 were hanged in the largest mass execution in U.S. history.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congressman Alexander Ramsey told Lincoln in 1864 that he would have received more re-election support in Minnesota had he executed all 303 warriors.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln responded, "I could not afford to hang men for votes." Lincoln called for reform of federal Indian policy but prioritized the war and Reconstruction.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Changes were made in response to the Sand Creek Massacre of November 1864, prioritizing peaceful administration of Native affairs and condemning those encroaching on Native territory, but not until after Lincoln's death.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ran for re-election in 1864; the Democratic nominee was former general McClellan.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Republican Party selected Andrew Johnson, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] To broaden his coalition to include War Democrats as well as Republicans, Lincoln ran under the new label of the National Union Party.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody stalemates and Confederate victories such as the Battle of the Crater damaged Lincoln's re-election prospects, and many Republicans feared defeat.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln prepared a confidential memorandum pledging that, if he should lose the election, he would "co-operate with the President-elect, as to save the Union between the election and the inauguration; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterwards".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Victories at Atlanta in September and in the Shenandoah Valley in October turned public opinion, and Lincoln was re-elected with 55.1 percent of the popular vote as well as 212 electoral votes to McClellan's 21.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Grant continued to weaken Lee's forces, efforts to discuss peace began.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephens, the Confederate vice president, and two other Confederate officials met with Lincoln and Seward at Hampton Roads.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln refused to negotiate with the Confederacy as a coequal, and the only agreement reached at the meeting concerned the exchange of prisoners.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's second inauguration took place on March 4, 1865; historian Mark Noll places his second inaugural address "among the small handful of semi-sacred texts by which Americans conceive their place in the world"; it is inscribed in the Lincoln Memorial.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] A month later, on April 9, Lee surrendered to Grant at Appomattox, signaling the end of the war.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] It triggered a series of subsequent surrenders across the South—in North Carolina, Alabama, and the trans-Mississippi Theater—and finally at sea with the surrender of the CSS *Shenandoah* in November 1865.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Reconstruction began before the war's end, as Lincoln and his associates considered the reintegration of the nation, and the fates of Confederate leaders and freed slaves.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] When a general asked Lincoln how the defeated Confederates were to be treated, Lincoln replied, "Let 'em up easy"; he focused not on blame for the war but on rebuilding.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Determined to reunite the nation and not alienate the South, Lincoln urged that speedy elections under generous terms be held.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] His Amnesty Proclamation of December 8, 1863, offered pardons to those who had not held a Confederate civil office and had not mistreated Union prisoners, if they signed an oath of allegiance.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln led the moderates in Reconstruction policy and was opposed by the Radicals, under Thaddeus Stevens, Charles Sumner and Benjamin Wade, who otherwise remained Lincoln's allies.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Southern states fell, they needed leaders while their administrations were being restored.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Tennessee and Arkansas, Lincoln appointed Andrew Johnson and Frederick Steele, respectively, as military governors.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Louisiana, Lincoln ordered Nathaniel P.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Banks to promote a plan that would reestablish statehood when 10 percent of the voters agreed, but only if the reconstructed states abolished slavery.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democratic opponents accused Lincoln of using the plan to ensure his and the Republicans' political aspirations.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals denounced his policy as too lenient and passed their own plan, the 1864 Wade–Davis Bill, but Lincoln pocket-vetoed it.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals retaliated by refusing to seat elected representatives from Louisiana, Arkansas, and Tennessee.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] After implementing the Emancipation Proclamation, Lincoln increased pressure on Congress to outlaw slavery nationwide with a constitutional amendment.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] By December 1863 an amendment was brought to Congress.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Senate passed it on April 8, 1864, but the first vote in the House of Representatives fell short of the required two-thirds majority.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Passage became part of Lincoln's re-election platform, and after his re-election, the second attempt in the House passed on January 31, 1865.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] After ratification by three-fourths of the states in December 1865, it became the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, abolishing "slavery [and] involuntary servitude, except as a punishment for crime".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln announced a Reconstruction plan that involved short-term military administration, pending readmission under the control of southern Unionists.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] He also signed Senator Charles Sumner's Freedmen's Bureau bill that set up a temporary federal agency designed to meet the immediate needs of former slaves.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law opened land for a lease of three years with the ability for the freedmen to purchase title.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Eric Foner argues that "Lincoln did not see Reconstruction as an opportunity for a sweeping political and social revolution beyond emancipation.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] He had long made clear his opposition to the confiscation and redistribution of land." However, the Lincoln scholar Phillip S.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Paludan suggests that at the end of his life Lincoln was moving towards a more radical position, particularly with regards to freedmen's rights.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Wilkes Booth was a well-known actor and a Confederate spy from Maryland; although he never joined the Confederate army, he had contacts within the Confederate secret service.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] After attending Lincoln's last public address, on April 11, 1865, in which Lincoln stated his preference that the franchise be conferred on some Black men, specifically "on the very intelligent, and on those who serve our cause as soldiers", Booth plotted to assassinate the President.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] When Booth learned of the Lincolns' intent to attend a play with Grant, he planned to assassinate Lincoln and Grant at Ford's Theatre.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and his wife attended the play *Our American Cousin* on the evening of April 14.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the last minute, Grant decided to go to New Jersey to visit his children instead.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] At 10:15 pm, Booth entered Lincoln's theater box, crept up from behind, and fired at the back of Lincoln's head, mortally wounding him.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's guest, Major Henry Rathbone, momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] After being attended by Charles Leale and two other doctors, Lincoln was taken across the street to Petersen House.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] He remained in a coma for nine hours and died at 7:22 am on April 15.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was wrapped in a flag and placed in a coffin, which was loaded into a hearse and escorted to the White House by Union soldiers.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Johnson was sworn in as president later that day.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two weeks later, Booth was located, shot, and killed at a farm in Virginia by Sergeant Boston Corbett.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] From April 19 to 20, Lincoln lay in state, first in the White House and then in the Capitol rotunda.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The caskets containing Lincoln's body and the body of his third son Willie then traveled for two weeks on a funeral train following a circuitous route from Washington D.C. to Springfield, Illinois, stopping at several cities for memorials attended by hundreds of thousands.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many others gathered along the tracks as the train passed with bands, bonfires, and hymn singing or in silent grief.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Historians emphasized the widespread shock and sorrow, but noted that some who had hated Lincoln celebrated his death.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Walt Whitman composed four elegies to Lincoln, including "When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd" and "O Captain!
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was buried at Oak Ridge Cemetery in Springfield and now lies within the Lincoln Tomb.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln redefined the political philosophy of republicanism in the United States.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Because the Declaration of Independence says that all men have an unalienable right to life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness, he called it the "sheet anchor" of republicanism, at a time when the Constitution was the focus of most political discourse.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] He presented the Declaration as establishing equality as a foundational principle for the United States, which had a significant impact on social and political movements in the U.S. into the 20th century.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a Whig activist, Lincoln was a spokesman for business interests, favoring high tariffs, banks, infrastructure improvements, and railroads, in opposition to Jacksonian democrats.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Nevertheless, Lincoln admired Andrew Jackson's steeliness and patriotism, and adopted the Jacksonian "belief in the common man".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a young man, Lincoln was a religious skeptic.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, he was deeply familiar with the Bible; throughout his public career, he often quoted scripture.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] His three most famous speeches—the House Divided Speech, the Gettysburg Address, and his second inaugural address—all contain such quotes.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the 1840s, Lincoln subscribed to the Doctrine of Necessity, a belief that the human mind was controlled by a higher power.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the death of his son Edward in 1850, Lincoln more frequently expressed a dependence on God.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] He never joined a church, although he and his wife frequently attended First Presbyterian Church in Springfield, Illinois, beginning in 1852.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] While president, Lincoln often attended services at the New York Avenue Presbyterian Church in Washington, D.C.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] The death of his son Willie in February 1862 may have caused him to look toward religion for solace.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's frequent use of religious imagery and language toward the end of his life may have reflected his own personal beliefs or might have been a device to reach his audiences, who were mostly evangelical Protestants.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Sources differ in how they describe his religious beliefs.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephen Mansfield describes "an atheist or religiously skeptical Lincoln" as "the prevailing view", although he argues that "there was a spiritual journey of some kind in Abraham Lincoln's life".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Richard Carwardine writes that "Many elements of the inner Lincoln, including his personal faith ... necessarily remain a puzzle".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's last words were, as reported by his wife, "There is no place I so much desire to see as Jerusalem".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Michael Burlingame, Lincoln was described as "awkward" and "gawky" as a youth.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] In adolescence he was tall and strong, participating in jumping, throwing, wrestling, and footraces, and demonstrating exceptional strength.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Burlingame notes that Lincoln's clothes "were typically rough and suited to the frontier", with a gap between his shoes, socks, and pants that often exposed six or more inches of his shin; "he cared little about fashion".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln was a slender six feet four inches, with a high-pitched voice.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] While he is usually portrayed bearded, he did not grow a beard until 1860 at the suggestion of 11-year-old Grace Bedell; he was the first U.S. president to do so.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Herndon described Lincoln's face as "long, narrow, sallow, and cadaverous", his cheeks as "leathery and saffron-colored".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln described himself as having a "dark complexion, with coarse black hair".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although Lincoln's features were said to be "unpleasant to behold," Walt Whitman "wrote that Lincoln's face was 'so awful ugly it becomes beautiful.'" Lincoln's detractors also remarked on his appearance.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Among the illnesses that Lincoln is either documented or speculated to have suffered from are depression, smallpox, and malaria.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] He took blue mass pills, which contained mercury, to treat melancholy or hypochondriasis; this could have resulted in mercury poisoning.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] Several claims have been made that Lincoln's health was declining before his assassination, as photographs of Lincoln appear to show weight loss and facial changes.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p02] It has been proposed that he could have had a rare genetic disorder such as Marfan syndrome or multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] In surveys of U.S. scholars ranking presidents since 1948, the top three presidents are generally Lincoln, George Washington, and Franklin D.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] A 2004 study found that scholars in history and politics ranked Lincoln number one, while legal scholars placed him second after Washington.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Kennedy, and Ronald Reagan were the top-ranked presidents in eight public opinion surveys by Gallup.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's assassination made him a national martyr.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] He was viewed by abolitionists as a champion of human liberty.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Many, though not all, in the South considered Lincoln to be a man of outstanding ability.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] In the New Deal era, liberals honored Lincoln as an advocate of the common man who they claimed would have supported the welfare state, and Lincoln became a favorite of liberal intellectuals across the world.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] The high point came in 1922 with the dedication of the Lincoln Memorial on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Black orator and former slave Frederick Douglass stated that in "his company, I was never reminded of my humble origin, or of my unpopular color", and Lincoln has long been known as the Great Emancipator.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] By the late 1960s, some Black intellectuals denied that Lincoln deserved that title.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lerone Bennett Jr. won wide attention when he called Lincoln a White supremacist in 1968.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] He noted that Lincoln used ethnic slurs and argued that Lincoln opposed social equality and proposed that freed slaves voluntarily move to another country.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Defenders of Lincoln highlighted his condemnation of slavery and his contributions to its abolition, casting his delays and racist rhetoric as concessions to political necessity rather than reflections of his personal beliefs.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has also been characterized as a folk hero and as "Honest Abe".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] David Herbert Donald opined in his 1996 biography that Lincoln was endowed with the personality trait of negative capability, attributed to extraordinary leaders who were "capable of being in uncertainties ... without any irritable reaching after fact and reason".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has often been portrayed by Hollywood, almost always in a flattering light; the film historian Melvyn Stokes writes that "moviemakers have commonly used Lincoln primarily as a metaphor for ideas and values they approved".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's portrait appears on two denominations of United States currency, the penny and the $5 bill.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] He appears on postage stamps across the world, including in Ghana, Honduras, China, Haiti, Nicaragua, Colombia, and Argentina.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] He has been memorialized in many town, city, and county names, including the capital of Nebraska.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] The United States Navy has named three vessels after Lincoln, including the *Nimitz*-class aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln* (CVN-72).
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., is one of the most visited National Park Service sites in the country.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Memorials in Springfield, Illinois, include the Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum, Lincoln's home, and his tomb.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] A carving of Lincoln appears with those of three other presidents on Mount Rushmore, which receives about 3 million visitors a year.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] A statue of Lincoln completed by Augustus Saint-Gaudens stands in Lincoln Park, Chicago, with recastings given as diplomatic gifts standing in Parliament Square, London, and Parque Lincoln, Mexico City.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Several states commemorate "Presidents' Day" as "Washington–Lincoln Day".
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has been extensively portrayed in media.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Early works, such as *Abraham Lincoln's Clemency* (1910), attempted to mythologize him, emphasizing his mercifulness.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Works from the Great Depression era, such as *Young Mr.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln* (1939), embellished his early struggles and folksiness.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] The 1938 play *Abe Lincoln in Illinois* won a Pulitzer Prize and was adapted in film.
[src:colorado-territory/abraham-lincoln-p03] After a marked decrease in film portrayals between 1941 and 1999, Daniel Day-Lewis won the Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal in *Lincoln*, a 2012 biographical film directed by Steven Spielberg.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] On May 30, 1854, the Kansas–Nebraska Act created the Territory of Nebraska and Territory of Kansas, divided by the Parallel 40° North (168th Avenue in present-day Adams County).
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] The future Adams County, Colorado, occupied a strip of northern Arapahoe County, Kansas Territory, immediately south of the Nebraska Territory.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] "Colonel Jack" Henderson built a ranch, trading post, and hotel on Henderson Island in the South Platte River in Arapahoe County, Kansas Territory.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Jack Henderson was the former editor and proprietor of the Leavenworth (Kansas Territory) Journal and an outspoken pro-slavery politician who had been accused of vote fraud in eastern Kansas.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Henderson sold meat and provisions to gold seekers on their way up the South Platte River Trail to the gold fields during the Pike's Peak Gold Rush.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Henderson Island was the first permanent settlement in the South Platte River Valley between Fort Saint Vrain in the Nebraska Territory and the Cherry Creek Diggings in the Kansas Territory.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Jack Henderson eventually returned to eastern Kansas and fought for the Union in the American Civil War.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Henderson Island is today the site of the Riverdale Regional Park, formerly known as the Adams County Regional Park and Fairgrounds.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] The eastern portion of the Kansas Territory was admitted to the Union as the State of Kansas on January 29, 1861, and on February 28, 1861, the remaining western portion of the territory was made part of the new Colorado Territory.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] The Colorado Territory created Arapahoe County, on November 1, 1861, and Colorado was admitted to the Union on August 1, 1876.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] In 1901, the Colorado General Assembly voted to split Arapahoe County into three parts: a new Adams County, a new consolidated City and County of Denver, and the remainder of the Arapahoe County to be renamed South Arapahoe County.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] A ruling by the Colorado Supreme Court, subsequent legislation, and a referendum delayed the creation of Adams County until November 15, 1902.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Governor James Bradley Orman designated Brighton as the temporary Adams County Seat.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Adams County originally stretched 160 miles (260 kilometers) from present-day Sheridan Boulevard to the Kansas state border.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] On May 12, 1903, the eastern 88 miles (142 kilometers)-wide section of Adams County was transferred to the new Washington County and the new Yuma County, reducing the length of Adams County to the present 72 miles (116 kilometers) and its area to the present 1,184 square miles (3,070 km2).
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] On November 8, 1904, Adams County voters chose Brighton as the permanent county seat.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] A 1989 vote transferred 53 square miles (140 square kilometers) of Adams County to the City and County of Denver for the proposed Denver International Airport, leaving the densely populated western portion of the county as two oddly-shaped peninsulas.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Adams County lost the tip of its northwest corner when the consolidated City and County of Broomfield was created on November 15, 2001.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 1,184 square miles (3,070 km2), of which 1,168 square miles (3,030 km2) is land and 16 square miles (41 km2) (1.4%) is water.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Adams County surrounds (and surrendered the land for) most of Denver International Airport which are in the City and County of Denver.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] As of the 2020 census, the county had a population of 519,572.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Of the residents, 25.7% were under the age of 18 and 11.1% were 65 years of age or older; the median age was 34.4 years.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] For every 100 females there were 101.9 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 100.9 males.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] 96.0% of residents lived in urban areas and 4.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] The racial makeup of the county was 55.8% White, 3.4% Black or African American, 1.8% American Indian and Alaska Native, 4.5% Asian, 0.2% Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander, 16.8% from some other race, and 17.6% from two or more races.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race comprised 41.7% of the population.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] There were 178,525 households in the county, of which 38.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 23.6% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] About 20.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 7.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] There were 186,544 housing units, of which 4.3% were vacant.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Among occupied housing units, 66.5% were owner-occupied and 33.5% were renter-occupied.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.0% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.9%.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] As of the 2000 census, there were 363,857 people, 128,156 households, and 92,144 families residing in the county.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] The population density was 305 people per square mile (118 people/km2).
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] There were 132,594 housing units at an average density of 111 per square mile (43/km2).
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] The racial makeup of the county was 77.29% White, 2.97% Black or African American, 1.19% Native American, 3.21% Asian, 0.12% Pacific Islander, 11.73% from other races, and 3.49% from two or more races.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] 28.19% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] There were 128,156 households, out of which 37.80% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.80% were married couples living together, 12.10% had a female householder with no husband present, and 28.10% were non-families.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] 21.20% of all households were made up of individuals, and 5.50% had someone who was 65 years of age or older living alone.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] The average household size was 2.81 and the average family size was 3.27.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] In the county, the population was spread out, with 28.60% under the age of 18, 10.30% from 18 to 24, 34.00% from 25 to 44, 19.40% from 45 to 64, and 7.80% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] For every 100 females, there were 102.80 males.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 102.10 males.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] The median income for a household in the county was $47,323, and the median income for a family was $52,517.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Males had a median income of $36,499 versus $28,053 for females.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] The per capita income for the county was $19,944.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] About 6.50% of families and 8.90% of the population were below the poverty line, including 10.90% of those under age 18 and 7.30% of those age 65 or over.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] In 2000, the largest denominational groups were Catholics (with 60,429 members) and Evangelical Protestants (with 25,552 members).
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] The largest religious bodies were the Catholic Church (with 60,429 adherents) and the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (with 6,808 adherents).
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Adams County has a Board of Commissioners that operate as a collective governing board.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] There are five members that form the Board of Commissioners with each elected to represent a district or portion of the county.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] There are other elected officials that oversee an aspect or department of county operations.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Adams County lies within the 17th Judicial District which is represented by District Attorney Brian Mason.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Adams County is predominately Democratic, not having voted Republican since Ronald Reagan in 1984.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] In 2016, Hillary Clinton won the county without a majority, becoming the first Democrat to do so since her husband Bill Clinton in 1992.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] In the 2020 election, Joe Biden easily won the county with a majority of the vote, a percentage similar to Barack Obama in 2012 and 2008 but with a much larger vote count.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Despite its Democratic majority, Adams County is significantly less Democratic than most other counties in the Denver metro area, frequently swinging towards the national trend.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Despite Biden's overwhelming victory in 2020, the county swung hard back towards Trump in 2024, reducing the Democratic margin of victory from nearly 20% to under 10%.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] This came even as Colorado failed to swing as hard as most other states.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] The county is also home to the Westminster campus of Front Range Community College, the largest community college by enrollment in Colorado.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Up until 1999 when Colorado ceased coding license plates by county, Adams County used the following codes on license plates issued to passenger vehicles: TE-UF, GA-GG, SAA-SEW, and SEY-TZZ.
[src:colorado-territory/adams-county-colorado] Adams County was featured as the fictional rival of South Park's peewee hockey team in the *South Park* episode "Stanley's Cup".
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The **Territory of Colorado** was an organized incorporated territory of the United States that existed from February 28, 1861, until August 1, 1876, when it was admitted to the Union as the 38th State of Colorado.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The territory was created during the onset of the American Civil War in the wake of the Pike's Peak Gold Rush, which brought the first large concentration of settlers from the east to the region.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The war stifled growth, but following the war mining grew more industrialized and fueled the economy.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The construction of railroads further improved the economy.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The boundaries of the newly designated Colorado Territory were very similar to those of the modern State of Colorado.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The Provisional Government of the Territory of Jefferson was an extralegal and unrecognized United States territory that existed in the Pike's Peak mining region from October 24, 1859, until it yielded to the new Territory of Colorado on June 6, 1861.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The Jefferson Territory included all of the present State of Colorado and portions of the present states of Kansas, Nebraska, Utah, and Wyoming.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The people were desirous of a closer government than those five territories provided.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Congressional grant of territorial status for the region was delayed by debate over the legality of chattel slavery.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The deadlock was broken by the Civil War in which enough Democratic senators from seceding states resigned from the Senate to give control of both houses to the Republicans, clearing the way for admission of new territories.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The State of Kansas was created on January 29, 1861 formalizing the separation of the western portion of the now defunct Kansas Territory.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Three new territories were created in as many days: Colorado (February 28), Nevada (March 1), and Dakota (March 2).
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Colorado Territory was officially organized by Act of Congress on February 28, 1861 (12 Stat.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] 172), out of lands previously part of the Kansas, Nebraska, Utah, and New Mexico territories.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The name *Colorado* was chosen for the territory after first considering *Idaho*.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] It had been previously suggested in 1850 by Senator Henry S.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Foote as a name for a state to have been created out of present-day California south of 35° 45'.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Abraham Lincoln appointed William Gilpin of Missouri the first Governor of the Territory of Colorado and he arrived in Denver City on May 29, 1861.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Jefferson Territory Governor Steele, peacefully transitioned the provisional government to Gilpin's authority.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The Colorado General Assembly first met on September 9, 1861, and created 17 counties for the territory on November 1, 1861.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] In 1861 following the beginning of the American Civil War, there were several small disputes and skirmishes between confederate supporters and union supporters.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] In August, Governor Gilpin organized the 1st Colorado Infantry.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] He encouraged the business of Denver to help outfit the new army on the belief that the federal government would provide funds.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] After racking up $375,000 in bills and failing to convince the federal government to pay out the Denver businesses the people called for a change in leadership.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Slough led the group to New Mexico Territory in February–March 1862.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] There they fought in the battles of Apache Canyon, Glorieta Pass and Peralta.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Slough resigned in April 1862 and was replaced by Major John M.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] On March 26, 1862 John Evans was appointed by Abraham Lincoln as the second governor of the territory.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] After Evans took the governorship, many of the debts Gilpin had incurred were paid by the federal government.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Anti-native sentiment grew during the Civil War years.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Exterminationist ideology, led in Colorado by Evans and Chivington, advocated for the total eradication of all native people in the territory.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] In response to their mistreatment, many bands of natives massacred and looted settlers and travelers around the territory.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Black Kettle and Roman Nose were leaders in the hostility.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Chivington committed the Sand Creek Massacre and Evans was forced to resign the following spring.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] During the Colorado War natives succeeded in blockade which cut off communication and severely restricted food supply.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Nearly every ranch between Denver and Nebraska was burnt and its occupants raped and killed.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The end of the civil war changed the nature of the white struggle against the natives because soldiers came from the east with better equipment to build forts.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] President Andrew Johnson appointed Alexander Cummings governor of Colorado Territory on October 17, 1865.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Evans still enjoyed strong support in Colorado which challenged Cummings' popularity.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Cummings' term was embroiled with much drama between himself and Samuel Hitt Elbert who was Secretary of the Territory of Colorado.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] At the core of the drama was the statehood issue.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Cummings did not immediately support statehood, and Elbert was part of the statehood faction.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] This issue was highly contentious and divided the people and the press in 1865.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Cummings advocated for the rights of colored people, another contentious issue, but the legislature upheld a ban on suffrage outside white males and prevented public schooling for colored people.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Political division between Golden and Denver grew through the 1866 election for the territorial delegate.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Cummings supported Alexander Cameron Hunt to be the territorial delegate in opposition the republican nominee from Denver.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Cummings denied the authority of the territorial election board, counted the results himself and declared Hunt the winner.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] A mob threatened to lynch Cummings and he moved to Golden.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The United States Congress did not recognize anyone as the duly elected delegate for the territory.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Cummings' term was plagued with allegations of political corruption which were characteristic of the reconstruction.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] For example, he paid his daughter, who did not live in Colorado at the time, $1,800 ($39580 inflation adjusted) for clerical work.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Cummings resigned in April 1867 and was replaced by Hunt.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Like Cummings, Hunt was an anti-statehood leader.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Hunt served as governor until June 1869.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] His term focused on negotiation with the native tribes.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] While Hunt was traveling, he appointed Frank Hall to act in his place.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Hall was the longest serving Secretary of the Territory of Colorado.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Many attempts were made to form a state governing the Colorado Territory.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] These began in the 1850s prior to the formation of Jefferson Territory and were thwarted for a variety of reasons until 1876 when Colorado became a state.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The United States Congress passed the Admission Act for the territory in late 1865, but it was vetoed by President Andrew Johnson.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] President Grant advocated statehood for the territory in 1870, but Congress did not act.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The Colorado Territory began as 95% male.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] However, the war and subsequent mining troubles limited population growth.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The 1865 census counted 27,931 but the count was contentious with pro-statehood groups claiming the population maybe as high as 40,000.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The population of 1870 was nearly the same as 1860.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Prostitution was common but sometimes led to animosity between citizens and brothels.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Through the civil war, Colorado was a one party Republican state.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Following the war, a minority democrat party formed.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Prior to the construction of railroads Coloradans used wagons to transport goods and messages.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] These began as irregular services, but starting in 1861 several regular wagon lines operated multiple days a week.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Colorado's economy increased by approximately threefold from 1865 to 1871.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The first telegraph line out of the territory began construction in 1861 and was completed from Denver to Julesburg, Colorado in October 1863.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] In 1865, a telegraph line through Fort Collins, Colorado reached Salt Lake City, Utah from Denver.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The economic boom of mining shifted the balance of power to the mining areas near Central City.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] In 1861, the towns planned the Colorado Central railway as a local rail network to support the mining industry.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] However the project was not started until 1865 and choose Golden as the hub.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Moffat led a capital raise to build the Denver Pacific Railroad northward to Cheyenne from Denver.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] In June 1870, the rail line was completed which gave Denver an economic advantage over the other Colorado towns.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] In 1867, the Union Pacific Railroad laid its tracks west to Julesburg, Colorado.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The Union Pacific linked up with the Central Pacific Railroad at Promontory Summit, Utah, on May 10, 1869, to form the First transcontinental railroad.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The Kansas Pacific arrived two months later to forge the second line across the continent.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] In 1871, William Jackson Palmer began the Denver and Rio Grande Western Railroad which connected Denver to Pueblo and beyond.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] He founded Colorado Springs the same year.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Only private banking was available in Colorado Territory until 1865 when First National Bank opened in Denver.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Chaffee and David Moffat were executives at the bank.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Oil was first extracted in the territory in 1861.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Kerosene began to be refined in Florence, Colorado.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The mint value of gold extracted in Colorado through 1862 was $30 million ($968 million inflation adjusted).
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] However the industry was not nearly as profitable as the miners hoped and many were unemployed.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The territory sought to improve the industry by creating a mint in Denver.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] On April 21, 1862 the United States Congress authorized the construction of the Denver Mint.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The Civil War's strain on the economy resulted in stagnation.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Thousands left their placer mines which had quickly become unprofitable and became soldiers for $15 per month ($537 inflation adjusted).
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] In addition to legitimate mining, others staked claims and then sold the rights to these claims as speculative assets to investors on the east cost.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] For the claimants this was sometimes more profitable than actually mining.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] In 1864, news of the large investments in Colorado mines sparked an idea to pay off the federal debts incurred due to the civil war by nationalizing the mines.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Naturally, the speculative miners opposed the scheme.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] By the end of the war, it had been settled that the mines would not be nationalized.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The scare did not dampen investment as millions continued to flow into highly speculative mining companies.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Some few operations turned enormous profits, but many turned into wild west stories of inept management and waste.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] In reality, the technology available was not sufficient turn reliable profits from gold and silver mining.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Following the Civil war, stamp mills and smelters began to be used more frequently.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] However these systems were highly inefficient and many went out of business.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Some individuals made a living panning the waste.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Labor quickly appreciated in value with some miners making $5 per day.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] This may have occurred due to the large number of laborers needed nationally to build railroads.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] By 1868, Central City was the hub of gold quartz mining with $50,000 weekly production ($1209 thousand inflation adjusted).
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] As capital intensive production scaled up the number of miners in Colorado diminished but profits rose sharply.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Through the 1860s additional silver and iron deposits were discovered at multiple locations around Colorado.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The territorial legislature met on a nearly annual basis.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The mountain towns lead most of the legislative decisions.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] The only towns granted special charters were Black Hawk, Denver, Central City, and Georgetown.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] In 1865, the legislature ensured the legality of gambling.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Colorado City: July 7 until August 14, 1862.
[src:colorado-territory/colorado-territory] Denver: December 9, 1867 until statehood on August 1, 1876.
